Release Plan - SEADS Android
CMPS 115 Fall 2016

Initial  Release [1.0.0]
 revision 2 [Nov 22, 2016]

High level goals:

    + Build up the Android application, mimicking the existing iOS Application.
    + Improve upon the current features in order to provide a better experience
      for our users.
    + Engage users with data visualization and provide meaningful outcomes.
    + Setup backend support capabilities independent of SEADS web team's progress.


Sprint 1:

	[8] As a user, I want to see my electricity usage in the form of a graph so that I can see how much energy I have been using.
	[8] As a user, I want to see a list of my devices so that I can tell which devices have been consuming power. 
	[5] As a user, I want to see my current and recent electricity cost so that I can understand the trend of my power usage. 
	[1] As a designer, I want a splash screen so that the user is not left starting at a black screen during a cold boot.

Sprint 2:

	[8] As a user, I want to see the rates I will be charged when I run appliances at a given part of the day, so I know when is the best time to use my big energy items.
	[5] As a user, I want to find out my historical power usage within the house in the form of a graph so I understand my current usage and save money.
	[3] As a user, I want to be able to edit which room show up on my home screen, so that I can see information about the rooms I care about most.
	[2] As a user, I want to be able to view my highest power consumption device so I can recognize what areas I can save money on.
	[2] As a user, I want to see an introduction on the first run of the app so that I understand how and why to use this app.

Sprint 3:

	[8] As a user, I want to be able to view current data in the form of a live-updating graph for each registered room in my house.
	[5] As a user, I want to look back at my history and compare how I have done in the past on saving power and money so I can strive to keep improving in the future.
	[5] As a user. I want to be able to sign up and login so that I have my data saved across sessions in a secured way.
	[3] As a user, I want to be able to setup and register my devices so that I can view the status for each of my device.
	[2] As a user, I want to be able to logout and clear data so that I can use the application with another account/house.

Product Backlog:

	As a developer, I want to test with a Raspberry Pi device so that I can get actual data on my mobile application.
	As a user, I want to know the average cost of running all of my devices across the day so that I can save money and reduce energy usage.
